<subSubSection id="C37B6523FFD8FF94FF46169A7801FD9C" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDE36A8FFD8FF94FF46169A7801FD9C" blockId="7.[192,1440,387,571]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis id="B915EABAFFD8FF94FF46169A7C79FE3C" bold="true" box="[192,325,387,411]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This species is an anomaly. The forewing pattern is unlike any other species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C614D2BFFD8FF94FB6A169A78A5FE3C" authorityName="Lafontaine and Poole" authorityYear="1991" box="[1260,1433,387,411]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Graphidaceae" genus="Megalographa" kingdom="Fungi" order="Ostropales" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B915EABAFFD8FF94FB6A169A78A5FE3C" box="[1260,1433,387,411]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Megalographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whereas the genitalia appear to be indistinguishable from those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C614D2BFFD8FF94FC5316BD79B3FE1C" box="[981,1167,419,443]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Graphidaceae" genus="Megalographa" kingdom="Fungi" order="Ostropales" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="agualaniata">
<emphasis id="B915EABAFFD8FF94FC5316BD79B3FE1C" box="[981,1167,419,443]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">M. agualaniata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The species can easily be recognized within 
<taxonomicName id="4C614D2BFFD8FF94FE3A16DA7F57FE7C" authorityName="Lafontaine and Poole" authorityYear="1991" box="[444,619,451,475]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Graphidaceae" genus="Megalographa" kingdom="Fungi" order="Ostropales" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B915EABAFFD8FF94FE3A16DA7F57FE7C" box="[444,619,451,475]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Megalographa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the elongated, narrow, tapering stigma, not the usually bilobed or two-lobed stigma of the other species in the genus. The sexes are similar. The male genitalia are like those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C614D2BFFD8FF94FF5B151D7CA0FDBC" box="[221,412,515,539]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Graphidaceae" genus="Megalographa" kingdom="Fungi" order="Ostropales" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="agualaniata">
<emphasis id="B915EABAFFD8FF94FF5B151D7CA0FDBC" box="[221,412,515,539]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">M. agualaniata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="135A2A2DFFD8FF94FE2D151A7F3EFDBC" box="[427,514,515,539]" captionStart="Figure 9–14" captionStartId="6.[192,276,1783,1805]" captionTargetBox="[210,1421,195,1754]" captionTargetId="figure-23@6.[192,1445,194,1776]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 9–14. Male genitalia of Megalographa spp. and Lophoplusia sp. 9) M. monoxyla, Cochabamba, Incachaca, Bolivia. 10) M. agualaniata, Venezuela. 11) M. bonaerensis, Curitiba, 920 m, Paraná, Brazil. 12) M. biloba, Verdugo, California. 13) M. talamanca, Reserva los Nimbulos, 3150 m, Cerro de la Muerte, San José, Costa Rica. 14) Lophoplusia sp., Kauai, Hawaii." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5352578" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5352578/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
), but the uncus is slightly stouter and the mesial bulge in the vesica is positioned closer to the base because the basal part of the vesica is much shorter in 
<taxonomicName id="4C614D2BFFD8FF94FBF9153D780AFD9C" box="[1151,1334,547,571]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Graphidaceae" genus="Megalographa" kingdom="Fungi" order="Ostropales" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="culminicola">
<emphasis id="B915EABAFFD8FF94FBF9153D780AFD9C" box="[1151,1334,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">M. culminicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
